        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-09 09:03:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthis patch sit on my local repository for ages, I think we might want to have it",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d8ceefca9eec62d0a8cb6f714834e1199d07c1fe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-09 20:28:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(3 inline comments)\n\nThis is a good fix, and I think we can probably do a lot more similar changes to reduce the size of ldlm locks (in separate patches of course).  I think with a minor change of struct packing it would be possible for this change to save another 8 bytes in all of the structs that are using portals_handle.\n\n\nI'd be thrilled to see similar improvements in later patches for other commonly used structs (e.g. ldlm_resource, ptlrpc_request, ptlrpc_reply_state, lu_object_header, cl_page, cl_lock, etc).  An excellent tool for this is called \"pahole\" (from the \"dwarves\" RPM package) that examines structures for packing issues.  I found the following quite useful:\n\n  pahole -RS -H2 lustre/obdclass/obdclass.ko\n  pahole -C ldlm_lock lustre/obdclass/obdclass.ko\n\nIt would be great to get struct ldlm_lock below 512 bytes so that it can pack into page-sized allocations more efficiently.  Other important structures may also see some benefits from similar shrinkage.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "bc818fc4453e5f273c396281344d4d5e3eba62e6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-09 20:42:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "011a6d01aa45230fed080486834c982f470d4c81",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2011-12-09 22:31:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 5.7/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/ca052aec-22a5-11e1-aee6-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "6d924aeb9d0cfa7d7b9d4a6f8ef37a2bb1e3bd3b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-09 23:04:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI don't object to using h_in:8 to keep GCC happy, since this is what was used in the previous code.  I don't think there is a danger from exceeding 2^24 byte allocations.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "848088e1bc8f69e4726da653094a93966114d76d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-10 00:51:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)\n\nreply inline",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "08dc45fd4b44ea8350bd54ad3a74c67b2bf61821",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-10 01:59:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThe size of spinlock_t depends on many different CONFIG parameters, though I admit I don't know which ones are enabled by default in distro kernels.\n\nSince the  32-bit atomic_t refc variable always the portals_handle it is more likely to pack well regardless of the kernel configuration.\n\nIt would be interesting to see what a recursive pahole check reports for ldlm_lock forthr packing. I didn't check this.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
